04224nam a22005535i 9780822390688DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19911991ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223906887 a10.1515/97808223906882doi  a(DE-B1597)552326  a(OCoLC)1226678715  a(OCoLC)1144321596  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPR473b.M55 1990 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a820.9/00912201 aMiller, J. Hillis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTropes, Parables, and Performatives /cJ. Hillis Miller. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgements -- t1. D. H. Lawrence: The Fox and the perspective glass -- t2. Franz Kafka and the metaphysics of alienation -- t3. Wallace Stevens' poetry of being -- t4. Williams' poetry of resignation -- t5. Thomas Hardy: a sketch for a portrait -- t6. Williams' Spring and All and the progress of poetry -- t7. History as repetition in Thomas Hardy's poetry: the example of "Wessex Heights" -- t8. Parable and performative in the Gospels and in modern literature -- t9. Mr Carmichael and Lily Briscoe: The rhythm of creativity in To the Lighthouse -- t10. Thomas Hardy, Jacques Derrida, and the "Dislocation of Souls" -- t11. Heart of Darkness revisited -- t12. Topography and tropography in Thomas Hardy's "In Front of the Landscape" -- t13. Impossible metaphor: (Stevens' "The Red Fern" as example) -- t14. When is a·Primitive like an Orb? -- t15. Prosopopoeia in Hardy and Stevens -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTropes, Parables, Performatives collects J. Hillis Miller's essays on seven major twentieth-century authors: Lawrence, Kafka, Stevens, Williams, Woolf, Hardy, and Conrad. For all their evident differences, these essays from early to late explore a single intuition about literature, which may be framed by three words: "trope," "parable," and "performative."Throughout these essays Miller is fascinated with the tropological dimension of literary language, with the way figures of speech turn aside the telling of a story or the presentation of a literary theme. The exploration of this turning leads to the recognition that all works of literature are parabolic, "thrown beside" their real meaning. They tell one story but call forth something else.Miller further agrees that all parables are fundamentally performative. They do not merely name something or give knowledge, but rather use words to make something happen, to get the reader from here to there. Each essay here attempts to formulate what, in a given case, the reader perfomatively enters by way of parabolic trope.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822390688zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822390688423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822390688.jpg  a978-3-11-071360-2  DUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles